member.example:
The following demonstrates the usage of

in
an endpoint registration and handler:

    endpointRouteBuilder.NewVersionedApi(EndpointConstants.GetFileClassificationsGroupName)
    .MapGroup(EndpointConstants.FileClassificationsEndpoint)
    .WithTags(EndpointConstants.FileClassificationsTag)
    .WithName(EndpointConstants.GetFileClassificationsName);

Example for creating a request:

    var request = new GetFileClassificationRequest
    {
    Name = EndpointConstants.GetFileClassificationsGroupName
    };

Below is an example of how to access and use GetFileClassificationsGroupName:

    string groupName = EndpointConstants.GetFileClassificationsGroupName;
    Console.WriteLine(groupName); // Output: "Get File Classifications"

This can also be used as part of the API version group definition:

    IVersionedEndpointRouteBuilder versionedApi =
    endpointRouteBuilder.NewVersionedApi(EndpointConstants.GetFileClassificationsGroupName);

Below is an example of how to use FileClassificationsTag when setting up endpoint routing:
_ = apiGroup.MapGet("/", async ([FromServices] FilesContext filesContext, [FromServices] GetFileClassificationsHandler handler, CancellationToken cancellationToken) => await handler.HandleAsync(filesContext, cancellationToken)) .Produces<IReadOnlyCollection<GetFileClassificationsResponse>>() .Produces(401) .Produces(403) .WithName(EndpointConstants.GetFileClassificationsName) .WithTags(EndpointConstants.FileClassificationsTag);
This tag will categorize the endpoint for API documentation or Swagger UI, ensuring clear grouping under the "File Classifications" category.

To map the endpoint in your application, use the following example:

    var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
    var app = builder.Build();
    app.UseFilesClassificationsApplicationServices();
    app.Run();
